<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<org.eclipse.epf.uma:TaskDescription xmi:version="2.0" xmlns:xmi="http://www.omg.org/XMI" xmlns:org.eclipse.epf.uma="http://www.eclipse.org/epf/uma/1.0.6/uma.ecore" xmlns:epf="http://www.eclipse.org/epf" epf:version="1.5.1" xmi:id="-bigV5_22TEElVb2SO4enSg" name=",_qmkTEL-YEd2e1-cAeXIm5A" guid="-bigV5_22TEElVb2SO4enSg" changeDate="2008-12-01T12:19:52.773+0100">
  <mainDescription>&lt;P class=MsoNormal style=&quot;MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt&quot;>&lt;SPAN style=&quot;FONT-SIZE: 10pt; mso-ansi-language: EN-US&quot;>&lt;FONT face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;>Having in mind that the purpose of this task is to decide how to obtain the services, all the decisions taken will be influenced by the type of company which is developing the composition.&lt;SPAN style=&quot;mso-spacerun: yes&quot;>&amp;nbsp; &lt;/SPAN>After this task, the description of each abstract service will be encouraged with information about the best option to obtain the service. &lt;?xml:namespace prefix = o ns = &quot;urn:schemas-microsoft-com:office:office&quot; />&lt;o:p>&lt;/o:p>&lt;/FONT>&lt;/SPAN>&lt;/P>&#xD;
&lt;P class=MsoNormal style=&quot;MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt&quot;>&lt;SPAN style=&quot;FONT-SIZE: 10pt; mso-ansi-language: EN-US&quot;>&lt;FONT face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;>The technique “Defining a Service Sourcing Policy” can be used in conjunction with these steps to perform this task. The obtained table will be used to add more information to the abstract services descriptions tables. &lt;o:p>&lt;/o:p>&lt;/FONT>&lt;/SPAN>&lt;/P></mainDescription>
  <sections xmi:id="_UBUgLMHrEd2B2LAvnwDruw" name="List own services which could be used " guid="_UBUgLMHrEd2B2LAvnwDruw">
    <sectionDescription>&lt;P class=MsoNormal style=&quot;MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt&quot;>&lt;SPAN lang=ES-TRAD style=&quot;FONT-SIZE: 10pt&quot;>&lt;FONT face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;>If the company developing the composition is a services developer enterprise, the first step is to take services list (from the internal catalogue) and indicate which of them can be used. This is important if the development team wants to use internal services which will offer more profit and trust for the company. &lt;?xml:namespace prefix = o ns = &quot;urn:schemas-microsoft-com:office:office&quot; />&lt;o:p>&lt;/o:p>&lt;/FONT>&lt;/SPAN>&lt;/P>&#xD;
&lt;P class=MsoNormal style=&quot;MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt&quot;>&lt;SPAN lang=ES-TRAD style=&quot;FONT-SIZE: 10pt&quot;>&lt;FONT face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;>Note for companies which DO NOT develop services: In the case that the enterprise does not develop any web service (and it is not a short term objective), the only solution is to use third party services to include them in the composition, so this step is not performed.&lt;o:p>&lt;/o:p>&lt;/FONT>&lt;/SPAN>&lt;/P></sectionDescription>
  </sections>
  <sections xmi:id="_UBUgK8HrEd2B2LAvnwDruw" name="Decide which legacy systems may be used " guid="_UBUgK8HrEd2B2LAvnwDruw">
    <sectionDescription>&lt;P class=MsoNormal style=&quot;MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt&quot;>&lt;SPAN lang=ES-TRAD style=&quot;FONT-SIZE: 10pt&quot;>&lt;FONT face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;>The second step is to list all the legacy systems available, so developers will be able to analyse which of them might be used. Other issue to be analysed is the feasibility of wrapping those legacy system and use them as web services in the composition. The cost associated to this task may not be negligible and has to be weighed up against the benefit. &lt;?xml:namespace prefix = o ns = &quot;urn:schemas-microsoft-com:office:office&quot; />&lt;o:p>&lt;/o:p>&lt;/FONT>&lt;/SPAN>&lt;/P></sectionDescription>
  </sections>
  <sections xmi:id="_UBUgLcHrEd2B2LAvnwDruw" name="Identify abstract services without possible candidates " guid="_UBUgLcHrEd2B2LAvnwDruw">
    <sectionDescription>&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot; style=&quot;MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt&quot;>&#xD;
    &lt;font face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;>&lt;span style=&quot;FONT-SIZE: 10pt; mso-ansi-language: EN-US&quot;>Developers have to gather all the&#xD;
    real services information available and analyse which abstract services haven’t candidates and can be developed&#xD;
    depending on company’s strategies.&lt;/span> &lt;span lang=&quot;ES-TRAD&quot; style=&quot;FONT-SIZE: 10pt&quot;>Brief descriptions of known&#xD;
    services or those included in system requirements can be used to determine if there are candidates for all the abstract&#xD;
    services descriptions.&lt;span style=&quot;mso-spacerun: yes&quot;>&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/font>&#xD;
&lt;/p></sectionDescription>
  </sections>
  <sections xmi:id="_UBUgKsHrEd2B2LAvnwDruw" name="Look for third party services " guid="_UBUgKsHrEd2B2LAvnwDruw">
    <sectionDescription>&lt;span&#xD;
style=&quot;FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: 'Times New Roman'; mso-fareast-font-family: 'Times New Roman'; mso-ansi-language: EN-US; mso-fareast-language: EN-US; mso-bidi-language: AR-SA&quot;>Although&#xD;
the company is able to develop services, there will be cases when the best option is to use third party services.&lt;/span>&#xD;
&lt;span lang=&quot;ES-TRAD&quot;&#xD;
style=&quot;FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: 'Times New Roman'; mso-fareast-font-family: 'Times New Roman'; mso-ansi-language: ES-TRAD; mso-fareast-language: EN-US; mso-bidi-language: AR-SA&quot;>One&#xD;
of the cases would be if the needed service is out of the scope of the domains the company works on, or if the service&#xD;
development is not going to be profitable. All the cases have to be identified in such a way the development team was able&#xD;
to decide which services should be consumed.&lt;/span></sectionDescription>
  </sections>
  <purpose>&lt;span&#xD;
style=&quot;FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: 'Times New Roman'; mso-fareast-font-family: 'Times New Roman'; mso-ansi-language: EN-US; mso-fareast-language: EN-US; mso-bidi-language: AR-SA&quot;>The&#xD;
purpose of this task is to decide how to obtain the services&lt;/span></purpose>
</org.eclipse.epf.uma:TaskDescription>
